[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, integration depth across multiple care-team systems, and human-care-management backstop)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is a Tuesday in March. Maria is 67. Maria has type 2 diabetes (diagnosed 14 years ago, currently on metformin and a once-weekly GLP-1), hypertension (on lisinopril and amlodipine), stage 3a chronic kidney disease (eGFR around 50, trending slowly), atrial fibrillation (on apixaban with a recent dose adjustment because of the kidney function), mild osteoarthritis in both knees, and (since last fall) macular degeneration in her right eye. Six weeks ago, after months of escalating fatigue and a hospitalization for what turned out to be a non-ST-elevation myocardial infarction, Maria had a coronary stent placed. She was discharged from the hospital nine days later than originally planned because of a brief AKI bump from the contrast load and because her cardiac rehab evaluation got rescheduled twice. She came home with sixteen prescriptions, a referral to cardiology for a follow-up in two weeks, a referral to nephrology for the kidney trajectory, a standing order for cardiac rehab three times a week, a recommendation to start seeing a registered dietitian for the diabetes-and-cardiac-and-renal medical-nutrition-therapy puzzle, a note to follow up with ophthalmology about the AMD, and a vague suggestion to "talk to her primary care doctor about everything" within thirty days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thirty days have now passed. Maria has been to cardiac rehab once. She missed the follow-up cardiology visit because the appointment got booked at a time she could not arrange a ride. She has not seen the nephrologist because the soonest available appointment is in eleven weeks. She has not seen the dietitian because she does not understand which dietitian she is supposed to see, the discharge paperwork mentioned three different names, and the one she did call referred her to someone else who has since stopped taking her insurance. She has not seen ophthalmology because she does not remember being told to. She has not refilled the apixaban. She has refilled the metformin but at her old dose, not the slightly reduced dose her cardiologist suggested verbally during the hospital stay (the change never made it to her active medication list because the resident who suggested it left service the next morning). The blood pressure cuff she was sent home with is still in its box because she is not sure how to log the readings or who is supposed to see them. She has gained four pounds, which may or may not be water; she does not know who to tell. The home-health nurse came twice in week one, once in week two, then a different nurse came in week three and asked questions the previous nurse had already asked, then no one came in week four, and Maria was not sure whether the home-health benefit had ended or whether the agency had simply lost track of her.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria has six clinicians who consider her "their patient." None of them know about most of the above. The cardiologist's office is following her through the cardiology-follow-up workflow, which means they are aware she missed the appointment and have a task in someone's queue to call her, but they do not know about the apixaban gap. The nephrologist has not yet seen her, so Maria is functionally not in their workflow at all. The primary care office is the closest to a quarterback role, but the PCP last saw Maria for an annual physical six months ago and has not had a clinical encounter since the hospitalization; the PCP's medical assistant has Maria's discharge summary in an inbox queue with 200 other discharge summaries, sorted by recency, and Maria's specific items have not been triaged. The cardiac-rehab program has Maria in their no-show queue but has not flagged her to her PCP. The home-health agency has her in their "lost contact" workflow but has not yet contacted the discharging hospital. The pharmacy has noticed the apixaban refill gap but the system that would alert the prescriber has been intermittently broken for two months and the alerts have been silently failing. The hospital's care-transitions team handed Maria off to her primary care office at discharge plus seven days, per protocol; the handoff was a structured note in the record and a phone call to a voicemail that no one has returned.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria, meanwhile, is at home, has a vague sense that she is supposed to be doing several things, has a stack of paperwork on her kitchen table, has not slept well in three days because she is anxious about all of this, and is mostly trying to keep up with feeding her dog. Her daughter (who lives an hour away and is the listed emergency contact) called the PCP's office last week to ask what Maria is supposed to be doing; the receptionist said she would have someone call back, and no one has. The daughter is now considering taking time off work to drive down and try to sort it out herself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is care coordination in the United States, which is to say, this is mostly not happening.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The numbers are not subtle. Patients with multiple chronic conditions account for a disproportionate share of healthcare cost, hospitalization risk, and adverse-event exposure. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS, AHRQ, and the National Council on Aging publish data on multi-morbidity prevalence and cost; specific figures vary by year and definition --> Care fragmentation across providers and settings (the average Medicare beneficiary with multiple conditions sees a meaningful number of clinicians and fills prescriptions at multiple pharmacies in a year) is correlated with poor outcomes, with care-transition periods (the days and weeks immediately after a hospital discharge or specialty referral) being especially high-risk. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care fragmentation, transitions of care, and 30-day readmission risk is extensive; specific figures vary --> Referrals are lost at meaningful rates between primary care and specialty care, with completion rates that vary substantially by specialty, by health system, and by patient sociodemographic factors. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on referral completion includes studies showing leakage rates that vary substantially; specific figures depend on the population and the referral type --> Care plans handed to patients at discharge or at specialty-visit conclusion are frequently not understood, not actionable, or both, with literacy gaps, language gaps, and cultural-fit gaps compounding the problem. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on patient-facing care-plan comprehension and actionability is documented in patient-experience and health-literacy research --> Care managers (RNs, social workers, community health workers) employed by health systems, payers, and value-based-care organizations are doing meaningful work on this gap, but the workforce is thin, expensive, and geographically uneven; care managers carry caseloads in the range of dozens to a few hundred patients each, depending on the population's complexity, and the time per patient is the dominant scaling constraint. <!-- TODO: verify; care-manager caseload data is documented by CMSA, ACMA, and other professional organizations; specific figures vary by population and program -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools tried to address this in three waves. The first wave, roughly the early 2010s, was patient-portal-based care plans (read-only documents the patient could view in a portal). The portals were used by a small fraction of patients, the documents were typically not updated after the visit they were created in, and the documents had no mechanism for tracking patient progress. The second wave, roughly the late 2010s, was care-coordination dashboards for clinicians (tools that aggregated cross-system data into a single pane of glass for care managers and PCPs). These tools improved care-team awareness in places they were deployed, but the patient-facing side remained mostly untouched, and the dashboards were only useful to the extent that the data feeding them was reliable, which (because of EHR-interoperability gaps) was variable. The third wave, starting around 2022, is conversational AI for care coordination, in shapes ranging from "patient-facing assistant that helps the patient navigate their care plan" to "care-manager-augmenting assistant that helps the human care manager handle a larger panel" to "hybrid assistant that does both." This third wave includes some careful, evidence-grounded products, some products with mixed evidence, and (as in the broader category) some products that probably should have stayed in the lab.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about building, carefully, a care coordination assistant that helps patients like Maria navigate the post-discharge or multi-specialist period without dropping the things that are clinically important, while augmenting (not replacing) the human care managers and clinicians who own the patient's overall care. The architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental health support) all converge here, and several new patterns enter the picture: cross-system care-plan reconciliation, referral-loop closure tracking, transition-of-care state machines, multi-clinician coordination with consent and scope-of-practice awareness, longitudinal task-tracking, and a level of integration with the human care-management workforce that is closer to "tightly coupled augmentation" than to "smart escalation."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps a patient with multiple conditions, multiple clinicians, multiple referrals, and (often) a recent care transition keep track of what they are supposed to be doing, why, and when, with the assistant pulling from the patient's actual care plan as recorded by their clinical team and surfacing it conversationally when the patient needs it. It tracks referral completion, follow-up-visit scheduling, medication-list reconciliation, home-health-and-community-resource engagement, and progress on care-team-defined goals. It escalates to a human care manager when the situation calls for it, and it delivers structured updates back to the care team so the team is not flying blind on the patient's between-visit reality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a care manager. The bot does not own the care plan. The bot does not modify the care plan. The bot does not make clinical decisions about what should be in the care plan. The bot does not perform clinical assessment. The bot does not adjust medications. The bot does not order tests or imaging. The bot is a navigation, tracking, surfacing, and warm-handoff tool whose authority extends to executing on care-plan items that the human clinical team has already authorized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a PCP. The bot does not provide primary care. The bot does not interpret symptoms. The bot does not provide clinical judgment about whether a new symptom is concerning. Symptom-related concerns route to triage (recipe 11.6) or to the patient's care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a single-system bot. The bot's defining characteristic is that it operates across systems: across multiple specialties within an institution; across multiple institutions where the patient receives care; across the patient's primary insurance, supplemental coverage, and (for Medicare patients) the layered Medicare-and-Medigap-or-Medicare-Advantage landscape; across home-health and community-based services; across the patient's social support network where appropriate. The integration burden is the dominant engineering cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. A high-utilizer Medicare patient with multiple chronic conditions has different coordination needs than a young adult navigating a recent cancer diagnosis, who has different needs than a parent coordinating a child's complex pediatric care, who has different needs than a working-age adult bouncing between physical-medicine specialists for a back injury. Most institutional deployments target a specific population segment (typically the high-utilizer multi-condition Medicare population for the cost-and-quality-impact case, or specific bundled-care or accountable-care populations for the value-based-care case).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in many quarters, not sprints. The integration work across EHRs, claims systems, scheduling systems, home-health systems, community-resource directories, and specialty workflows is multi-quarter. The care-team workflow integration is multi-quarter. The cross-clinician consent and scope-of-practice work is multi-quarter. Outcome demonstration is multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of its conversational responses. The value is in three places: the bot remembering things the patient cannot reasonably keep track of (sixteen medications, four upcoming appointments across three specialties, three referrals at varying stages of completion, two home-health touches scheduled for next week); the bot surfacing the right thing at the right time (the apixaban refill gap, the missed cardiology follow-up, the cardiac-rehab no-show pattern, the daughter's call that has not been returned); and the bot serving as a backstop for the human care-management workforce so that the workforce can scale to populations that would otherwise be unreachable. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on referral-loop closure rates, on medication-list reconciliation rates, on care-plan-item completion rates, on transition-of-care 30-day-readmission rates (with appropriate caution about attribution), and on patient-reported coordination experience is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Cross-System Care Plan Awareness, Longitudinal Task Tracking, and Hybrid Bot-Plus-Human Care Coordination
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools, And Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, is by its nature a multi-system multi-actor problem. The reason it has resisted digital tools for so long is structural. The patient's care plan is not in one place; it is in many places, often inconsistent across them, and frequently incomplete in any given system. The cardiologist's note has the cardiology plan. The PCP's chart summary has the PCP's view of the plan, which may or may not include the latest specialty inputs. The discharge summary captures one moment in time. The pharmacy has the medication-fill history but does not see the clinical reasoning. The home-health agency has its own plan of care. The patient has paperwork. None of these sources sees the whole picture, and reconciling them is, in practice, what care managers do for a living.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools tried to fix this by building shared dashboards, shared portals, and shared records. The shared-records approach (the "let us all use the same EHR" approach) worked well within a single integrated delivery network, less well across institutions, and not at all across the patient's full care landscape including community resources, social services, and the patient's own household. The shared-portals approach (the "patient sees their own care plan in a portal") suffered from the limitations noted above: portals are used by a fraction of patients, the documents are static, and the documents have no mechanism for tracking the patient's actual progress. The shared-dashboards approach (the "give care managers a single pane of glass") improved care-team awareness in deployed locations but did not solve the patient-facing side of the problem and did not extend reach to populations the workforce could not touch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can read across multiple data sources, generate coherent multi-document summaries, drive structured tool use against the systems where the data lives, and carry on a conversation with the patient about it in plain language. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can pull the patient's active care plan from the EHR, pull the patient's referral list and completion status from the referral-management system, pull the patient's medication list and recent fills from the pharmacy system, pull the patient's recent encounter activity and discharge summaries, pull the patient's open home-health and community-resource engagements, pull the patient's stated goals and preferences, reconcile the lot into a coherent picture, and surface it conversationally when the patient asks "what am I supposed to be doing this week?" The bot is not the care manager. The bot is the tool that extends the care manager's reach by handling the routine surface area, while flagging the cases where the human is needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static documents and dashboards" to "conversational interface backed by cross-system retrieval and reconciliation." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the consistency of cross-system reconciliation (the bot does not get tired, does not lose the discharge summary in an inbox, does not forget that the patient was referred to nephrology three weeks ago); the conversational accessibility of the care plan (the patient who would not log into a portal will, sometimes, type into a chat); and the operational-reach extension (the patient population that human care management cannot reach can be partially served by a bot-plus-human hybrid that the human workforce alone could not).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on the boundary between this recipe and the chronic disease coach (recipe 11.7). The chronic disease coach is condition-focused: it helps a patient manage diabetes, or hypertension, or heart failure, with condition-specific psychoeducation, behavior-change support, and care-plan-item tracking for that condition. The care coordination assistant is multi-condition and cross-clinician: it helps a patient navigate a portfolio of care items across multiple conditions, multiple clinicians, multiple care settings, and (often) a recent care transition. The two are complementary; many institutions deploy both, with the coach handling within-condition longitudinal coaching and the coordinator handling cross-condition portfolio management. They share consent-gated context and refer to each other when their respective scopes touch the boundary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on the boundary between this recipe and the human care manager. The bot does not replace the care manager. The bot extends the care manager's reach. In a well-designed deployment, the human care manager owns the patient's care plan from the patient-facing side, sets the priorities, makes the clinical-judgment calls, and intervenes when the situation needs human judgment; the bot handles the routine items, surfaces the patient's between-visit reality to the care manager, escalates the cases where human judgment is needed, and keeps the patient anchored to the care plan in moments when the human is not available. The hybrid is not "AI replaces care manager"; the hybrid is "AI lets the care manager be effective for a larger panel."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active conditions, current medications, current care plan items across all clinicians, open referrals and their status, scheduled visits, recent encounter activity, recent discharge events, current home-health engagements, current community-resource engagements, patient-stated goals and preferences, patient's legal-decision-maker and emergency-contact information where consented, patient's social-determinant-of-health profile where consented), access to the institutional and (with consent) external data sources that hold the care plan and its components, and a careful set of tools for retrieving, surfacing, tracking, and acting on care-plan items within the bot's authorized scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (the most common pattern), sometimes initiated by the bot per a scheduled care-plan touchpoint, sometimes triggered by a system event (the patient was discharged from a hospitalization, a referral was scheduled, a referral closed without a completed visit, a medication-fill gap exceeded a threshold), sometimes triggered by a care-team event (the care manager assigns a follow-up touchpoint, the PCP requests a between-visit check-in).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consent.** The patient is enrolled in the coordination program by their care team or self-enrolls through their portal, with documented consent that covers the bot's nature, the bot's scope, the privacy posture across the multiple care-team integrations, the data-sharing posture with each clinician on the care team (collected separately and revocable per clinician), and the crisis-pathway behavior. The first conversation does the disclosure work: the bot identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, explains what it can and cannot do (specifically that it is a navigation and tracking tool, not a care manager and not a clinician), names the human care-team availability, names the crisis resources, and describes the privacy posture in plain language. The patient acknowledges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan reconciliation.** On enrollment and on every meaningful care event (a discharge, a specialty visit, a new referral, a medication change, a goal change), the bot re-reconciles the care plan from its component sources and produces a coherent unified view. The unified view is not the source of truth (the source of truth is the institutional EHR and adjacent systems); the unified view is the bot's working representation, refreshed on a defined cadence with version stamping. Skip this discipline and the bot speaks confidently about a care plan that has been superseded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated conversations within scope.** The patient can engage at any time about within-scope topics: what is on the current care plan, what is the next item to do, why a particular item is on the plan, what is the status of a particular referral, what is the next appointment, how to prepare for an upcoming visit, what to expect after a recent visit, how to access community resources the care team has identified, how to engage home health, how to use the blood pressure cuff or the glucose meter, how to refill a medication. Out-of-scope topics route appropriately: clinical-symptom interpretation routes to triage (recipe 11.6); within-condition coaching routes to the chronic disease coach (recipe 11.7); mental-health support routes to recipe 11.8; FAQ-level questions route to recipe 11.1; benefits questions to recipe 11.5; appointment scheduling to recipe 11.2; refills to recipe 11.3; pre-visit intake to recipe 11.4.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral-loop tracking and closure.** The bot tracks every open referral the patient has, with status (referred, scheduled, completed, no-show, declined, expired, lost-to-follow-up), and surfaces follow-up actions: scheduling a referral that has not yet been scheduled, rescheduling a referral that was no-showed, escalating to the care manager when a referral is at risk of expiration, recording the patient's reason when a referral is declined. The referral-loop discipline is one of the bot's highest-value patterns; referral leakage is a measurable problem and the bot's structured tracking is a measurable mitigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition-of-care state-machine handling.** Transitions of care (hospital discharge, ED discharge, SNF discharge, post-procedure return home, transfer between facilities, transition between care settings) have time-windowed care plans with structured follow-up requirements. The bot tracks the transition-of-care state machine: was the transition-of-care visit scheduled within the appropriate window, was the medication reconciliation completed, was the discharge instructions review completed with the patient, was the home-health touch within the planned window, did the 30-day readmission window pass without an event. The state machine is institutional protocol-driven; the bot drives the patient-facing engagement and surfaces gaps to the care manager.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-list reconciliation support.** Across multiple clinicians prescribing for multiple conditions, the patient's medication list is one of the highest-risk artifacts for inconsistency. The bot surfaces the current medication list as recorded by the institution, asks the patient to confirm what they are actually taking, flags discrepancies for clinician review, and surfaces medication-related items (refill timing, medication-related side-effect questions, drug-drug interaction questions identified by the institution's clinical decision support) when they appear. The bot does not adjust medications; the bot surfaces and routes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Home-health and community-resource engagement.** Where the patient has active home-health visits, durable medical equipment in place, transportation services, meals-on-wheels engagement, social-services engagement, or other community-resource touchpoints, the bot tracks the engagement and supports the patient's interaction with those services: scheduling a home-health visit, reporting a missed home-health visit, reporting a problem with DME, escalating concerns about service quality or interruption.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-reported-outcome and patient-reported-experience capture.** The bot can administer brief patient-reported-outcome instruments (e.g., shortened symptom-burden surveys, brief functional-status measures, patient-experience-of-care measures) that complement the clinical data. The instrument selection is institutional-protocol-driven and reviewed by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Goal tracking and progress surfacing.** The bot tracks the patient's stated goals (typically captured at care-plan creation) and surfaces progress toward them periodically. The goals are not bot-generated; they are patient-and-clinician-co-created goals that the bot displays and supports.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-coordination support.** The bot surfaces, with patient consent, who is on the patient's care team, what each clinician's role is, when each was last seen, what the next contact is. The bot supports the patient's questions about who to contact for what.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm handoff to the human care manager.** The bot escalates to the human care manager when the situation calls for it: any out-of-scope clinical question, any concerning symptom disclosure, any complex care-plan question, any patient-stated frustration that exceeds the bot's scope, any signal of social-determinant-of-health distress (housing instability, food insecurity, transportation gap, financial-strain disclosure), any disclosure of cognitive or functional decline, any caregiver-strain disclosure, any patient request for a human, any low-confidence handling. The handoff is warm: full conversation context, no patient-restart, bridge-and-stay-present pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting (with patient consent).** Where the patient has consented to information sharing, the bot generates structured updates back to the care team: a weekly care-team digest summarizing engagement, items completed, items at risk, gaps surfaced, issues flagged for human review. The bot's role is not to replace the care manager's documentation; it is to give the care manager the patient's between-visit reality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance with appropriate framing.** The bot maintains conversation history and stated patient preferences. The bot is professional and warm; the bot does not simulate friendship or affection. The framing inherits from the chronic disease coach: warm but boundaried.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when appropriate.** Some patients improve and no longer need active coordination support. Some patients move to a different program or care setting. Some patients prefer human-only coordination. The bot supports a respectful transition with structured summary delivery to the care team and a clear path back if the patient wants to re-engage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a care coordination assistant," and let it engage with users about their care. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consistent cross-system data access.** Without structured tool calls into the EHR, the referral-management system, the pharmacy system, the home-health system, the community-resource directory, and the patient-preference store, the bot has no way to actually answer "what is the status of my nephrology referral." The bot will either hallucinate ("Your nephrology appointment is on April 15th"), apologize ("I do not have access to that"), or generalize ("Specialty referrals typically take..."). Each of these is bad. The structured tool surface is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-plan reconciliation across sources.** The patient's care plan in the cardiology system, the PCP system, the post-discharge document, and the patient's own understanding may all differ. The bot must reconcile these into a coherent view, with version awareness and clinician attribution; the generalist LLM either picks one source arbitrarily or averages across them in ways that lose specificity. The structured reconciliation pipeline is the architectural answer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no scope discipline about clinical decisions.** A generalist LLM, prompted to be helpful, will drift into providing clinical interpretation. "Should I take my apixaban with food?" "Why was my dose changed?" "Is this side effect normal?" Each of these has a correct answer for the specific patient, and the bot's correct answer is "let me get that question to the right clinician on your team," not a freestyled response. The scope discipline must be enforced explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-team scope-of-practice.** Different clinicians own different parts of the patient's care; the cardiologist owns the cardiac care plan, the nephrologist owns the renal care plan, the PCP owns the integrated overall plan, the dietitian owns the nutrition counseling. The bot's routing of patient questions has to respect this. A generalist LLM has no awareness of who owns what; the routing logic is institutional-protocol-driven and is encoded in tool calls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent-gated cross-system data sharing.** The patient may have consented to the bot accessing the cardiology system but not the mental health system. The patient may have consented to the bot sharing summaries with their PCP but not with their employer's wellness program. The bot's data access and data sharing must be enforced per-source per-clinician per-purpose; the generalist LLM has no awareness of these constraints, and a violation here is a privacy event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of transition-of-care protocols.** The 30-day-post-discharge window, the 7-day-post-discharge follow-up requirement, the 14-day-post-procedure check-in, the time-windowed components of bundled-care episodes: each is institutional-protocol-defined with structured timeline expectations. The bot must drive the engagement against the protocol; the generalist LLM has no protocol awareness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** The Charlson Comorbidity Index, the LACE readmission risk score, the HCC risk-adjustment categorization, scheduled-visit interval calculations, and similar are arithmetic on structured inputs. The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic clinical-rule tools encapsulate the computation; the LLM assembles inputs and surfaces results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social-determinant-of-health detection.** Patients sometimes disclose, in passing, that they cannot afford a medication, that their housing is unstable, that they are food-insecure, that they have no reliable transportation, that they are isolated. These disclosures are the most actionable signals the care team can receive, and they are not always recognized as such by a generalist LLM. The structured SDOH-detection-and-routing pipeline is part of the bot's value.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of caregiver dynamics.** Many patients with complex care needs are supported by a family caregiver (spouse, adult child, friend) who may be the actual operator of the patient's chat interface, may have authority to act on the patient's behalf in some domains and not others, and may be carrying their own stress-and-burden load. The bot's awareness of the caregiver and the caregiver's role is institutional-policy-driven.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to leave the conversation.** A generalist LLM in extended interaction will keep generating responses. The care coordination conversation has natural completion points (the patient's question is answered, the care-plan item is acknowledged, the warm handoff is initiated). The bot's conversation-ending heuristics are reviewed by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of reliability across long timescales.** Care coordination is not a single-conversation problem; it is a months-or-years-long longitudinal problem. The bot's behavior must be stable across long timescales: same care plan referenced consistently, same care-team awareness consistently, same goal awareness consistently. The longitudinal-context store and the reconciliation discipline are how this consistency is achieved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of partial information.** The bot will frequently encounter situations where one source has data, another source does not, and the patient's stated reality is a third thing. The bot's response in these situations is structured: surface the discrepancy, attribute the sources, route to a human for resolution if material. The generalist LLM tends to confabulate a unified view; the structured discrepancy-handling is the correct pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equity disparities in care coordination.** Care fragmentation is not equally distributed; it is worse for patients with limited English proficiency, for patients with low health literacy, for patients in geographic-access-poor areas, for patients without a stable PCP, for patients with multiple insurance types or coverage gaps, for patients with mental-health or substance-use comorbidity, for patients with cognitive impairment. The bot's per-cohort monitoring is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to defer to the human care manager.** The bot's authority extends to executing on care-plan items the human team has already authorized. New decisions, ambiguous situations, complex patient circumstances, and patient frustration that exceeds the routine all defer to the human. The default-to-defer policy is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis screening, companion-pattern avoidance, warm handoff to licensed clinicians. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system care-plan reconciliation as architectural primitive.** The bot's working representation of the patient's care plan is reconciled across multiple sources on a defined cadence and on every meaningful event, with version stamping and source attribution. The reconciliation pipeline is owned jointly by the care-management leadership, the EHR-integration team, and the IT data-engineering team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral-loop closure tracking as architectural primitive.** Every open referral is tracked with a state machine through the lifecycle (referred, scheduled, completed, no-show, declined, expired, lost-to-follow-up). The bot drives the patient-facing engagement through the lifecycle and surfaces gaps to the care manager. The referral-loop closure rate is a launch-gate metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition-of-care state-machine handling as architectural primitive.** Transitions of care have time-windowed protocols with structured follow-up requirements. The bot drives the patient-facing engagement against the institutional protocol and surfaces gaps. The 30-day-readmission rate is a relevant outcome metric (with appropriate caution about attribution).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-clinician scope-of-practice routing.** The bot's routing of patient questions respects clinician scope of practice: cardiology questions to cardiology, renal to nephrology, integrated questions to PCP, nutrition to the dietitian, mental health to the appropriate clinician. The routing rules are institutional-protocol-driven and reviewed by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system consent-gated data access and sharing.** Consent is collected per-source-per-clinician-per-purpose, is revocable per element, and is enforced operationally on every access. The audit trail captures the consent state at the time of every access.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-manager-augmenting workflow integration.** The bot is deployed as augmentation to the human care-management workforce, not as replacement. The integration is bi-directional: the care manager assigns touchpoints to the bot, the bot surfaces issues to the care manager, the care manager has visibility into the bot's interactions, the bot has visibility into the care manager's recent activities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinant-of-health detection and routing.** The bot detects SDOH signals (housing instability, food insecurity, transportation gap, financial strain, isolation, caregiver strain) and routes to the appropriate response: the care manager for case-management, the social work team for direct intervention, community-resource directories for self-service navigation. The detection language is reviewed by social-work clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Longitudinal-task-tracking with reliable persistence.** The bot's working state about open care-plan items, open referrals, open transitions, open patient-stated concerns, and open follow-ups must be reliable across months and years. The persistence layer and the reconciliation discipline are how this reliability is achieved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration burden is the dominant engineering cost.** Unlike the symptom checker (which can operate with relatively minimal chart context) or the chronic disease coach (which integrates with one or two clinical-data sources for the target condition), the care coordination assistant must integrate with the full range of care-plan-defining systems. EHRs (frequently more than one for patients who receive care across institutions), referral-management systems, pharmacy systems, home-health systems, durable-medical-equipment systems, transportation-services systems, community-resource directories, social-services systems, telehealth platforms, patient-portal systems, claims-and-eligibility systems. Each integration has its own data model, its own reliability profile, its own latency profile, and its own consent posture. The integration work is the bulk of the deployment effort.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The reconciliation problem is genuinely hard.** Different systems will disagree about the patient's medication list, will disagree about the patient's active referrals, will disagree about the patient's care-plan goals. The disagreement is not a data quality issue that will go away with effort; it is a structural feature of the multi-actor multi-system landscape. The bot's reconciliation discipline must handle disagreement explicitly, attributing sources and surfacing material discrepancies to humans for resolution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The scope discipline has more surface area than the other bots.** Care coordination touches every clinical specialty, every care setting, every social context. The temptation to expand the bot's scope is constant ("the bot already knows about cardiology; can it answer cardiology questions?"). Resisting the temptation, and routing scope-expansion questions to clinical-leadership and care-management leadership for explicit scope decisions, is a continuous discipline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The workforce-integration problem is more delicate than in the other bots.** Care managers are professional workers with specific scope-of-practice, specific licensure (RN, LCSW, etc., depending on the program), and specific workload expectations. Integrating the bot into their workflow without making them feel surveilled, displaced, or undermined is a workforce-relations problem as much as an engineering problem. Care managers who feel the bot is replacing them will not engage with it; care managers who feel the bot is augmenting them will become advocates and will provide the operational feedback that drives the bot's improvement. The deployment posture matters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent is more granular than in the other bots.** The patient's consent is not a single yes-or-no; it is per-source-per-clinician-per-purpose, often with state-specific layered constraints. The patient may consent to the bot accessing the cardiology and nephrology systems but not the behavioral-health system. The patient may consent to the bot sharing weekly summaries with the PCP but not with the cardiologist. The patient may revoke any of these consents at any time. The granular consent posture must be operationalized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient population is older, more complex, and less digitally-native on average than the chronic-disease-coach population.** Care coordination's highest-value population is multi-condition Medicare patients, many of whom are 70+, many of whom have variable digital comfort, many of whom rely on a family caregiver as the actual operator of digital interfaces. The bot's accessibility, reading-level, language, channel availability, and caregiver-handling discipline are all affected.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations matter significantly here.** Care coordination is, in part, a navigation service through institutional structures that vary in their accessibility for patients of different cultural and linguistic backgrounds. The bot's content adaptation, language coverage, and per-cohort outcome monitoring are not optional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver dynamics are central.** Many patients in this population have a family caregiver as the active operator. The caregiver may be authenticated with the patient's permission, may operate the chat on the patient's behalf, may have specific authorities (durable power of attorney for healthcare, healthcare proxy, etc.). The bot's awareness and handling of the caregiver is an institutional-policy-driven design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is harder than in single-condition coaching.** Care coordination affects outcomes through many channels (referral completion, medication adherence, transition-of-care follow-up, SDOH surfacing) and the attribution of any single outcome to the bot's contribution is a hard analytic problem. The institutional outcome-correlation pipeline acknowledges this and uses matched-cohort or quasi-experimental designs for the attribution claims.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical-leadership ownership is different from condition-specific coaching.** The care-coordination program is typically owned by a population-health or care-management leadership function rather than a specialty clinical leadership; the bot's clinical-content discipline is jointly owned by the care-management leadership and the relevant specialty leadership for the populations served.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningful but distributed.** A bot that fails to surface a critical care-plan item may contribute to a patient's adverse outcome; the attribution is harder than in mental-health support but not zero. The institutional malpractice carrier and care-management-program legal counsel are part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Value-based-care models reward care coordination.** The Medicare Shared Savings Program, Medicare Advantage, the various Innovation Center models (ACO REACH, primary-care models, bundled-care payment models, kidney-care models), and commercial value-based contracts all create financial incentives for effective care coordination. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS publishes information on value-based-care program participation and design; specific program details continue to evolve --> The economic case for care-coordination investment is stronger in value-based contracts than in fee-for-service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based care-plan exchange is maturing.** The HL7 FHIR specification provides standard resources for CarePlan, Goal, Task, ServiceRequest, Communication, Encounter, and other elements of a coordinated care representation. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 and beyond include the resources noted; specific implementation guides include the US Core implementation guide and several care-coordination-specific implementation guides --> Bot integrations build on FHIR where the institution's systems support it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and information-blocking rules expand cross-institution data access.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) and the ONC information-blocking provisions of the 21st Century Cures Act provide regulatory and technical pathways for cross-institution patient data access. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has progressed since the initial Common Agreement publication; specific details continue to evolve --> Bots operating across multiple institutions benefit from these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management workforce models are evolving.** Hybrid licensed-and-unlicensed care-management models, with RNs at the top of the team and community health workers, peer specialists, and bot-augmented coordination at the operational layer, are increasingly common. The bot's deployment posture in this evolving workforce model is an institutional decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-source reconciliation well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve from each source, the institutional reconciliation logic produces a unified view, the LLM produces conversational responses against the unified view with citations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused outcome research in digital care coordination is active.** Variability in adoption, engagement, cultural fit, and outcomes across patient demographics has been documented. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in digital care-coordination tool adoption and outcomes have been documented in studies of specific programs and populations --> Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination products at health-system and payer scale, with EHR integration, claims integration, and care-management workflow integration. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for core care-coordination platform capabilities and (sometimes) for the licensed-care-management workforce, and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
